node.text:
As some of you may know, someone has been aggressively stalking, harassing and impersonating me for the past year. This person has threatened me, slashed my tires, and done a bunch of other gruesome things that I don’t want to even talk about because I think that will give them satisfaction. This person has tried everything under the sun to try and ruin my reputation, humiliate me and break me down. They have involved my family members, my work and are continuing to impersonate me right now. I have a hard time feeling safe but like many of
you have found that training has been the only way I have been able to get through this. I posted a photo a few days ago with a gun. I wanted to clarify something, I am not a gun nut, but making multiple police reports and fbi reports and having them tell me there is nothing they can do until I am harmed I felt I needed a way to protect myself. So this is a video made by @fitdocproductions briefly going over a trip I made to Texas to tell them a little bit about my story and how to learn how to protect myself. Please have an open mind and understand where I am coming from. Also, PLEASE DO NOT SEND ANYONE PRETENDING TO BE ME MONEY! I would never ask you to do that! Thank you guys!

node.text: I rarely share my personal life on instagram. However this last weekend something happened that I wanted to share! Before you unfollow me thinking I am changing my content to fluffy romantic stuff, I’m not I just think it’s important to give you more of an understanding of who I am. My husband and I have been together since 2013 and we met in medical school. I wouldn’t even be on instagram writing this or have been a fitness model if it wasn’t for him. He’s been there supporting me and loving me for who I am every step of the way. Video done by the incredible @gilcoproductions!!!

node.text:
RIP Yiaya Xenia. I love you so much and learned so much from you. She was the American dream. She left a small village in Cyprus at 16 and moved to Detroit with my Papou. They worked their fingers to the bone to make a living. They wanted their children to be able to have the education and opportunities they never had and they achieved that. Every day I am thankful for all of the sacrifices you made and all of the obstacles you overcame to give all of us a better life. 

Ready or not, some day it will all come to an end.
There will be no more sunrises, no minutes, hours or days.
All the things you collected, whether treasured or forgotten
will pass to someone else.
Your wealth, fame and temporal power will shrivel to irrelevance.
It will not matter what you owned or what you were owed.
Your grudges, resentments, frustrations
and jealousies will finally disappear.
So too, your hopes, ambitions, plans and to-do lists will expire.
The wins and losses that once seemed so important will fade away.
It won't matter where you came from
or what side of the tracks you lived on at the end.
It won't matter whether you were beautiful or brilliant.
Even your gender and skin color will be irrelevant.

So what will matter?
How will the value of your days be measured?

What will matter is not what you bought
but what you built, not what you got but what you gave.
What will matter is not your success
but your significance.

What will matter is not what you learned
but what you taught.
What will matter is every act of integrity,
compassion, courage, or sacrifice
that enriched, empowered or encouraged others
to emulate your example.

What will matter is not your competence
but your character.
What will matter is not how many people you knew,
but how many will feel a lasting loss when you're gone.
What will matter is not your memories
but the memories that live in those who loved you.
What will matter is how long you will be remembered,
by whom and for what.

Living a life that matters doesn't happen by accident.
It's not a matter of circumstance but of choice.
Choose to live a life that matters.
